projects.background:
During my childhood, my family constantly fought over political differences. The fights got intense often, and I remember hiding in the bedroom, praying the sounds of quarreling would end soon. As a result, growing up, I became proudly politically indifferent, seeing anyone who engaged in political activities as a fanatic. However, as the old saying goes: “Just because you do not take an interest in politics doesn&#039;t mean politics won&#039;t take an interest in you.” It took me a decade of trying to escape from understanding politics to realize that freedom should not be taken for granted. Without us exercising the civic duty of maintaining, challenging, and participating in thoughtful democratic discussions and decision-making, the freedom we enjoy in everyday life can disappear in an instant. 

//

The advancement of social networks, and generative AI tools, while bringing many conveniences to our lives, have also made fake news more and more natural. The line between fact and fiction is now completely blurred, as is the line between truth and fake. The ability to arrive at a “fact” that most people can agree on seems almost impossible. Even within a like-minded group, having earnest conversations on societal topics had also become difficult, especially with cancel culture as the dominating solution for resolving a conflict. Surrounded by these situations in my daily life, I set my thesis as a journey to explore tools and methods that can possibly help initiate and/or facilitate honest conversations on complex topics within groups of people. 

//

While the thesis project is heavily influenced by my personal life experience as a Taiwanese living abroad, it parallels the world full of conflicts in which we all live. The project reflects my constant effort and hopes to find a mutual truth we can all agree on. 

//

&lt;&lt; RESEARCH &gt;&gt;

In a way, the thesis summarizes my one-year exploration inside this IMA Low Res graduate program. I came to this program to explore not only the various methods of making interactive media arts but also its experimental way as a Sino-American graduate program. By being in a program where half of the classmates are from China, and another half from mainly the United States, followed by onsite residencies in New York, Berlin, and Shanghai – I thought the program was a great place to conduct field research while also learn more about seeing &quot;truths&quot; from the two extremes that as a Taiwanese, I am stuck in (i.e., China vs. the US).

//

The research method was simple, including daily reading and news research on major internet forums and news sites in China, Taiwan, and the United States. I then compiled a list of “facts” seen extremely differently from the three. With the list in mind, I started asking strangers and friends around the world about their take on the stand and see if there’s a difference in understanding based on their nationality and frequently read news sources. With the results from those informal interviews, I designed the questions for the Miro board. Worth noting that the majority of the research of the project was done while living in New York City. 

//

During the last session of the program, which is a 5-week residency in Shanghai, China, I was able to conduct more in-depth research from a China perspective. The experience is fruitful, to say the least; I have learned so much and have yet to digest all the information I&#039;ve gained.

projects.technical_system:
This project is built using Miro Board, a privately owned whiteboard software/ online tool that is widely used by companies and educational institutions as a digital collaboration platform. The project&#039;s content is built using several internet-based news sources, as well as clip art illustrations from an open licensed Japanese website called Irasutoya. This particular way of building the project is my tribute to all the readymade arts before me and an attempt to make readymade digital art. I found the form of the project itself also connects to the recent boom in AI generative tools and the conversation around it.  

//

Miro board became my choice of platform because of its web friendliness, intuitiveness, and its mix of high-tech and low-tech at the same time – at least from my perspective. I particularly love its sticky notes function, which allows users to stick anywhere on the board and write in. This resonates with the usage of sticky notes in creating a physical “democracy wall” during many student movements and protests globally in the past few years. I also chose Miro because of the ability to see the live actions of all other users while everyone stays anonymous. While Miro board software comes with the ability to host live voting, I chose to build a visual and manual voting system because the action of each user’s computer mouse is what I find important as a part of the interaction and “discussion.”

projects.conclusion:
While the Miro Board was the main focus of my thesis journey, it is worth noting that I’ve explored several different ways of fostering difficult conversations throughout my time in this program. For instance, I’ve built a javascript-based Yes/No voting system on questioning the conversation around the swastika symbol by implementing the discourse on public and counter-public. I’ve also made a Raspberry Pi into a Wi-Fi antenna, to alter information on governmental and news websites, hoping that can intrigue people to rethink the information they absorbed without much questioning daily. Recently, I’ve also experimented with machine learning to build an interactive game where participants can win or lose based on whether the words they say to the computer are considered appropriate for the Communist Party of China. This last project is the most direct and aggressive, in which not many people felt comfortable participating due to the fear of getting into trouble. However, hopefully, the game’s symbolism helps trigger some conversation around censorship that is normalized in contemporary Chinese society. 

//

While I understand none of the projects mentioned above, including the Miro board, can truly help me resolve my bigger existential problems, the process of building them and sharing them with people at least helps shine a light on my concerns and gives me the opportunity and courage to start uncomfortable conversations that I truly care about with others.

projects.background:
Affective computing advancements have led numerous companies worldwide to focus on developing facial emotion recognition systems to enable artificial intelligence to predict human behavior. Major tech giants such as Amazon, Microsoft, and Google provide basic emotion analysis capabilities, while smaller enterprises like Affectiva and HireVue specialize in tailored applications for specific industries such as automotive, advertising, mental healthcare, and recruitment. Even MIT has dedicated affective computing groups striving to develop and assess innovative ways of integrating Emotion AI and other affective technologies to enhance people&#039;s lives.

Despite the existence of numerous articles highlighting the dangers and biases associated with facial recognition systems, many companies continue to employ them. This is particularly noticeable during the pandemic, as software like 4 Little Trees generates detailed reports on students&#039; emotional states for teachers and even assesses motivation and focus. However, it is important to recognize that &quot;It is not possible to confidently infer happiness from a smile, anger from a scowl, or sadness from a frown.&quot;

In a research paper by Barrett, Adolphs, Marsella, Martinez, and Pollak (2019), which reviews over 1,000 studies conducted over a span of two years, scientists from the Association for Psychological Science identified a wide array of expressions used to convey emotions. This variability makes it challenging to reliably infer someone&#039;s emotional state based on a limited set of facial movements. The paper highlights three significant limitations in scientific research that contribute to a general misunderstanding of how emotions are expressed and perceived through facial movements, thereby limiting the applicability of this scientific evidence: limited reliability, lack of specificity, and limited generalizability.
